        return createView

  )

In the above example if the user permission network.inventory-default is present and/or enabled from the RBAC API response, then the user will see these elements, otherwise they will be hidden.
As the Platform knows where these RBAC Contributions are coming from it is able to apply CSS rules with knowledge of what is running where and when.

The RBAC Core Plugin makes usage of AbsurdJS to construct the CSS from the provided "selectors". 

 Custom CSS for permissions

If permission flag "ignore" is setted as "true", body element will have class for this permission lookig as

 .intent--[permissionName]__[permission]

In permission name dots should be replaced by double underscore.  Example for "network.inventory-default" will look like

 .intent--networkinventory-defaultgRead

End result looking as follows.

 myPlugin.less

.intent--networkinventory-defaultgRead .dt-exportAll-btn .ds-label  

Check user permission from JS code

To check does user have a permission from JS file, use following:

 myPlugin.js

 amd module syntax
define([
	"dna-service!external/cisco.dna.core.rbac/rbac"
], function(rbac)  );
 es6 module syntax
import rbac from "dna-service!external/cisco.dna.core.rbac/rbac"

// ...

// now you can make use of rbac service APIs
var isPermitted = rbac.checkPermission("network.inventory-default", "gRead");

checkPermission will return "true", if user has the permission, "false" if does not have a permission and "null" if permission does not exist in API response.

To get all permitted operations by resource name
 amd module syntax
define([
	"dna-service!external/cisco.dna.core.rbac/rbac"
], function(rbac)  );
